message.content: Let $s_1$ be the side length of the first polygon and $s_2$ be the side length of the second polygon. The perimeter of the first polygon is $38s_1$ and the perimeter of the second polygon is $ns_2$ for some positive integer $n$. We set up the equation $38s_1=ns_2$. We know that $s_1=2s_2$ so we substitute to get $38(2s_2)=ns_2$. Simplifying gives $76s_2=ns_2$. Dividing by $s_2$ and rearranging gives $n=\boxed{076}$.
